00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:12.220
We were talking about this
symmetry reparameterization

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:12.940
invariance.

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:17.110
And what we showed last time
is that the Wilson coefficient

00:01:17.110 --> 00:01:20.410
of this operator is 1 to all
orders in perturbation theory

00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:21.970
because of that symmetry.

00:01:21.970 --> 00:01:24.160
The Wilson coefficient
of this operator is not.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:26.230
And I told you that
at leading log order,

00:01:26.230 --> 00:01:29.080
it would be given by some
expression like this.

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:31.720
But in general, this is just
the lowest order expression.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:35.532
And it gets
perturbatively corrected.

00:01:35.532 --> 00:01:36.990
It's actually known
at three loops.

00:01:40.430 --> 00:01:43.460
So let's continue.

00:01:43.460 --> 00:01:45.530
We've talked about
reparameterization invariance

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:47.060
for the Lagrangian.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:48.650
Reparameterization
invariance also

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:51.020
has important consequences
for operators.

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:04.040
So just like we wrote down
sub-leading Lagrangians,

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:06.110
we should also write
sub-leading currents.

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:10.009
So there's 1 over mq
supressed currents.

00:02:10.009 --> 00:02:11.660
And if you look
at those currents

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:15.463
and you construct them,
then you find, again,

00:02:15.463 --> 00:02:16.880
that reparameterization
invariance

00:02:16.880 --> 00:02:20.080
plays an important role.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:23.768
And again, there's relations
between Wilson coefficients.

00:02:27.260 --> 00:02:29.090
And what happens in
this case is actually

00:02:29.090 --> 00:02:33.800
that the leading order operator
had a Wilson coefficient,

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.640
the lowest order operator.

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:38.090
So the Wilson coefficients
of the subleading operators

00:02:38.090 --> 00:02:40.629
get related to that of
the leading operator.

00:02:50.120 --> 00:02:54.010
And I may give you a problem on
that on your next problem set.

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:58.650
But I haven't quite
made up my mind yet.

00:02:58.650 --> 00:03:00.662
So rather than go
through that, I

00:03:00.662 --> 00:03:02.370
want to talk about
some observables where

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:05.080
these operators played a role.

00:03:05.080 --> 00:03:07.563
So we've seen one example of
reparameterization invariance.

00:03:07.563 --> 00:03:08.980
And I think from
that one example,

00:03:08.980 --> 00:03:11.530
you would be able to
do other examples.

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:13.780
Let's talk about masses.

00:03:13.780 --> 00:03:15.720
These operators here
actually have an impact

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.080
on the masses of hadrons.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:24.120
If we think about the
mass of a heavy meson, h,

00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:28.470
there's a heavy quark
in that heavy meson.

00:03:28.470 --> 00:03:31.200
So we can pull out
that heavy quark.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:33.720
And then there's some remainder.

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:36.535
And we can characterize higher
order terms in this formula.

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:44.770
So let me first explain
what this lambda bar is.

00:03:44.770 --> 00:03:49.060
Our Lagrangian here, if
we're working at lowest order

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:55.810
in the theory, our Lagrangian
would be L0 of HQET plus,

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:58.090
for the light quarks,
they're basically

00:03:58.090 --> 00:04:03.475
just a QCD Lagrangian,
so for the light quarks

00:04:03.475 --> 00:04:04.100
and the gluons.

00:04:07.148 --> 00:04:09.740
So for the heavy
quark, we have HQET,

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:11.390
and then there would
be higher order

00:04:11.390 --> 00:04:13.973
terms that are 1
over m suppressed,

00:04:13.973 --> 00:04:15.140
which are the ones up there.

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:21.079
So the question is, if
we have this Lagrangian,

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:24.870
what is the mass of a heavy
state like the b meson

00:04:24.870 --> 00:04:26.810
or the d meson or the d star?

00:04:26.810 --> 00:04:29.370
And we can characterize that
by knowing the structure

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:31.430
of the Lagrangian.

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:35.300
So first of all, what about
this term, this lambda bar?

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:39.257
That term actually comes from
these parts of the Lagrangian.

00:04:39.257 --> 00:04:41.090
So if we take these
parts of the Lagrangian,

00:04:41.090 --> 00:04:44.570
we can calculate
the Hamiltonian.

00:04:44.570 --> 00:04:47.000
Let me call that H0.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.280
And the definition
of this lambda bar

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:58.537
is the thing that you get
by taking that Hamiltonian

00:04:58.537 --> 00:04:59.870
and letting it act on the state.

00:05:03.390 --> 00:05:05.930
So you can think that this is--

00:05:05.930 --> 00:05:08.390
if you like, you can think
that this state is just

00:05:08.390 --> 00:05:10.760
an eigenstate of
the Hamiltonian.

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:13.310
You get the energy.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:17.360
But since the Hamiltonian has
no heavy quark mass in it,

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:19.260
what you're getting
is some parameter,

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:21.510
which is traditionally called
lambda bar, that doesn't

00:05:21.510 --> 00:05:23.780
have a heavy quark mass in it.

00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:25.670
And so there's no heavy
quark mass in here.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:32.960
So it's independent of mq.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:37.160
It's also independent of spin.

00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:50.120
So B versus B star and
flavor B versus D. So

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:52.548
whether it's a B
meson, D meson, as long

00:05:52.548 --> 00:05:54.590
as we're in this limit
where both the bottom mass

00:05:54.590 --> 00:06:01.880
and the char mass
are heavy, if we're

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:04.460
thinking of this
expansion, then this

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:06.740
is a universal thing
just determined

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:08.468
by these Lagrangians.

00:06:08.468 --> 00:06:10.010
It's traditionally
called lambda bar.

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:12.830
And it's telling you that if
you think about this thing

00:06:12.830 --> 00:06:14.540
as having an order
mq piece, this

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:16.950
is the order mq to the 0 piece.

00:06:16.950 --> 00:06:18.740
The symmetry of the
theory is telling us

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:20.735
that this is a
universal constant.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:29.660
It does depend on
the state here,

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.030
although that state could
be connected to other states

00:06:32.030 --> 00:06:35.460
by spin symmetry
and flavor symmetry.

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:41.120
There was this quantum number
we talked about last time, which

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:44.330
we called SL for the spin of
the light degrees of freedom,

00:06:44.330 --> 00:06:47.800
and then pi for the parity of
the light degrees of freedom.

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:54.650
So it's the same
within every multiplet

00:06:54.650 --> 00:06:58.220
that we get from a fixed SL pi.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:00.722
But there's a different
value for each multiplet.

00:07:04.852 --> 00:07:06.560
So you'd have a
different value of lambda

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:10.760
bar for the B, D, B star B than
for the lambda B and the lambda

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:11.570
C, for example.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:17.200
So that's this term.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.680
We can also characterize
what's going on with this term

00:07:19.680 --> 00:07:21.720
by using this
Lagrangian here, the L1.

00:07:25.750 --> 00:07:28.660
So at order 1 over
MQ, we can figure out

00:07:28.660 --> 00:07:31.930
what kind of contributions
to the mass we're getting.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:34.870
h1 is just minus L1.

00:07:34.870 --> 00:07:37.060
You can think of it
now perturbatively.

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:39.370
So that just flips the
sign of what we had before.

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:06.240
And we get two parameters from
taking matrix elements here.

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:07.780
They get the following names.

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:24.000
And let me just do
everything here in terms of--

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:30.068
it's not totally
crucial, but it's

00:08:30.068 --> 00:08:31.860
a little easier to
interpret certain things

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:33.068
if we work in the rest frame.

00:08:33.068 --> 00:08:35.375
So I'll just work
in the rest frame.

00:08:35.375 --> 00:08:36.750
So if you work in
the rest frame,

00:08:36.750 --> 00:08:38.583
you should just think
of this as like giving

00:08:38.583 --> 00:08:40.500
some kind of measure
of the kinetic energy

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:42.780
that the heavy quark
gets wiggled by.

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:44.760
And that's called lambda 1.

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:47.040
This, again, is a matrix
element that doesn't know

00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:48.870
about the heavy quark mass.

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:52.260
And the heavy quark
mass in an explicit MQ.

00:08:52.260 --> 00:08:56.275
So this guy has dimension 2 if
you work out the dimensions.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.880
And then you can do the
same for the other operator.

00:09:03.880 --> 00:09:08.980
And here you have to
think a little bit harder.

00:09:08.980 --> 00:09:12.270
And if you think a
little bit harder,

00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:15.510
you can characterize
what the coefficients

00:09:15.510 --> 00:09:18.360
are for different spins.

00:09:18.360 --> 00:09:22.590
So there's some
Wilson coefficient.

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:23.940
And then we have this operator.

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:44.235
And this here is like sigma
dot B. I told you that before.

00:09:44.235 --> 00:09:45.610
And so you should
think of what's

00:09:45.610 --> 00:09:49.300
going on here as you have
sigma, which is giving the SQ,

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:50.750
and then you have a B field.

00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:53.992
And then it's a
question of what vector

00:09:53.992 --> 00:09:56.200
could be left over that the
B field could know about.

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:58.570
And it's basically SL.

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:04.750
So this guy here is
leading to the SQ.

00:10:04.750 --> 00:10:06.635
And this guy here is
leading to the SL.

00:10:11.870 --> 00:10:13.960
And so that's where
this SQ.SL comes from.

00:10:16.810 --> 00:10:20.040
So you can think about
other possibilities,

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:22.350
but you have to have
the right symmetry

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:24.270
structure under time
reversal and parity

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:25.650
and things like that.

00:10:25.650 --> 00:10:27.450
And that forces you
to use a spin here

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:31.230
for the B and not
something like the V.

00:10:31.230 --> 00:10:34.230
So this SQ.SL is something
that you can write out

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:39.060
as, remembering the definition
of it and its relation to J

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:41.910
squared.

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:45.270
You can write out
that factor like that.

00:10:45.270 --> 00:10:48.540
And then we can derive here
how this lambda 2 contributes

00:10:48.540 --> 00:10:52.410
to the differing
states, because we

00:10:52.410 --> 00:10:54.750
have a different
contribution for the B

00:10:54.750 --> 00:10:56.850
and the B star from
the lambda 2 guy,

00:10:56.850 --> 00:11:00.450
because it was violating
the spin symmetry.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:03.300
So the lambda 1 guy is going
to violate the flavor symmetry.

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:05.160
That's this 1 over MQ.

00:11:05.160 --> 00:11:06.840
And so charm quarks--

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:08.940
charm mesons and
bottom mesons will

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:11.010
get different
contributions from that.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:14.250
They have the same
lambda 1, but they

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:16.530
have a different connection
because it gets suppressed

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:19.210
by a different factor.

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:25.815
And then again for
the lamba 2, Lambda 2

00:11:25.815 --> 00:11:27.690
is a little bit different
because it actually

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:29.072
has mu dependents.

00:11:32.852 --> 00:11:33.810
That's not quite right.

00:11:33.810 --> 00:11:39.240
So it actually has MQ dependents
because the coefficient here

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:41.160
has mu dependents.

00:11:41.160 --> 00:11:43.810
So this operator doesn't
have any MQ dependence,

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:46.350
but the coefficient
does, remember.

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:48.710
The mu dependence cancels
and there's a left over MQ

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:53.691
dependence to the lambda 2, but
it's logarithmic MQ dependence.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:59.960
If I define it this way--

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:01.640
so that's why I wrote MQ there.

00:12:09.740 --> 00:12:11.990
So you could, as we
talked about last time,

00:12:11.990 --> 00:12:15.962
you could sum up the logs of
large logs and have this guy--

00:12:15.962 --> 00:12:17.420
you could re-sum
logs, if you want.

00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:19.295
So you could think of
these as you can re-sum

00:12:19.295 --> 00:12:20.450
logs inside this lambda 2.

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:28.280
So if we ignore those logs or
we imagine that we re-sum them

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:29.900
and we just look
at the remainder,

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:32.750
then we have the expectations
based on power counting

00:12:32.750 --> 00:12:35.090
for how big these things are.

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:36.740
And we just [? expect ?]
that they're

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:38.480
both given by the dimension.

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:40.310
And the only
[? dimensionful ?] parameter

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:43.533
around is lambda QCD
because the MQs can only

00:12:43.533 --> 00:12:45.950
occur in logarithms, and the
Wilson coefficient in nowhere

00:12:45.950 --> 00:12:48.580
else.

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:52.800
And these are
non-perturbative parameters.

00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:02.162
Lambda bar is also a
non-perturbative parameter.

00:13:02.162 --> 00:13:04.120
These ones have a little
more dynamics in them.

00:13:06.780 --> 00:13:10.280
So then we could go out
and write for our states

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:13.170
the results by putting
these things together.

00:13:13.170 --> 00:13:16.550
So we'd have M capital
B plub M little B

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:22.040
plus lambda bar lambda
1 over 2 and little B.

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:24.890
And if we go through the
spin structure there,

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:30.410
we get a 3/2 and then
lamba 2 logarithmic MB

00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:31.660
dependence over MB.

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:43.410
So when we start
with the B star,

00:13:43.410 --> 00:13:44.980
the first three
terms are the same.

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:48.030
And then this guy
comes in with a plus.

00:13:48.030 --> 00:13:51.850
And it's lambda 2
over MB over 2MB.

00:13:55.600 --> 00:14:03.520
And then the D states
are similar in turn.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:11.800
Lambda bar lambda 1 over 2M
term, and then these two terms

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:13.330
again.

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:17.218
Same spins, so it's lambda 2.

00:14:17.218 --> 00:14:18.760
And the only difference
is, now we're

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:28.500
evaluating the lambda 2 as
logarithm and charm dependence,

00:14:28.500 --> 00:14:29.000
OK.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.430
So there's some formulas
that are correct, actually--

00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:34.490
including all the way up
to 1 over M corrections.

00:14:34.490 --> 00:14:36.140
And you can see that
there's still sort

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:37.580
of a structure to these things.

00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:40.310
This is a universal
correction for all of them.

00:14:40.310 --> 00:14:43.730
These corrections are
universal between B and B star.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:45.935
And so the splitting
between B and B star

00:14:45.935 --> 00:14:48.660
is just given by this lambda 2.

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:50.600
That's what causes
the states to split.

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:52.920
So up to that level,
they're the same.

00:14:52.920 --> 00:14:55.095
And that's why the B and
B star are very degenerate

00:14:55.095 --> 00:14:56.345
and the masses are very close.

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:02.930
So you can form combinations
to cancel things out.

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:08.960
So you can take a kind of
spin average mass where

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:14.480
you take 3 times the vector
plus the scalar divided by 4.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:17.750
And if you do that, then you're
canceling out the lambda 2.

00:15:27.010 --> 00:15:29.360
And then you can also
form differences.

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:33.800
So if you looked at MV star
squared minus MB squared,

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:35.770
then the only thing that's
causing a difference

00:15:35.770 --> 00:15:40.060
is lambda 2.

00:15:40.060 --> 00:15:44.860
Numerically, this
is 0.49 GV squared.

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:50.980
And from our formula up
there, it's 4 lambda 2 of MB,

00:15:50.980 --> 00:16:00.020
so something like four
times 0.12 GV squared.

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:02.290
So that's the value
of this lambda

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:06.770
2 is 0.12 GV squared, which
is about lambda QCD squared.

00:16:06.770 --> 00:16:09.555
So our dimensional
analysis is working.

00:16:09.555 --> 00:16:11.680
And then you can do the
same thing for the D meson.

00:16:15.917 --> 00:16:17.750
Everything here works
beautifully, actually.

00:16:31.430 --> 00:16:33.100
Extract the value
of lambda 2 and you

00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:39.130
see there's a slight difference
because that difference can be

00:16:39.130 --> 00:16:40.834
attributed to the logarithms.

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:48.662
So if you take lambda
2 MB over lambda 2 MC,

00:16:48.662 --> 00:16:51.120
then the only thing that differs
is the Wilson coefficient.

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:54.450
So that's something
you can predict.

00:16:54.450 --> 00:17:00.890
So experimentally, if you take
the ratio of those two things

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:06.530
there, you get a
prediction like this one.

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:12.148
And if you plug in theory
like leading log RGE,

00:17:12.148 --> 00:17:13.565
then you're getting
alpha S of MB.

00:17:16.166 --> 00:17:17.290
Oh, sorry.

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:18.109
[INAUDIBLE]

00:17:23.749 --> 00:17:28.220
And this is 1.17.

00:17:28.220 --> 00:17:30.790
So that's for three
light flavors,

00:17:30.790 --> 00:17:33.500
which is the right thing to
do for the beta function.

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:37.150
So it's not so bad for a
leading log prediction.

00:17:37.150 --> 00:17:40.090
That's kind of the
accuracy you would expect.

00:17:44.090 --> 00:17:45.260
All right.

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:47.020
So we're really
understanding quite a bit

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:48.603
from our [INAUDIBLE]
[? instruction ?]

00:17:48.603 --> 00:17:51.280
of this effective
theory about the states,

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:55.570
and even make predictions for
the ratios of the mass divided

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:58.350
by that as something
preservative, which

00:17:58.350 --> 00:18:01.165
is kind of non-trivial.

00:18:01.165 --> 00:18:03.040
Perturbative up to the
order we were working.

00:18:03.040 --> 00:18:06.310
There would be corrections if
we continued in our series here.

00:18:06.310 --> 00:18:08.470
There could be some
non-perturbative corrections.

00:18:08.470 --> 00:18:11.530
But up to 1 over M,
the ratio of this

00:18:11.530 --> 00:18:15.463
to that, which is what I'd wrote
over there, is perturbative.

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:20.580
All right.

00:18:20.580 --> 00:18:23.040
So that's some phenomenology.

00:18:23.040 --> 00:18:24.840
It's kind of baseline
phenomenology

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:27.330
that we can do with
the Hamiltonian

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:31.770
or with Hamiltonian derived
from our subleading Lagrangian.

00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:35.010
There's other phenomenology
that we can do.

00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:38.045
And I'll mention some of the
most important phenomenology.

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:46.407
There's another
class of predictions

00:18:46.407 --> 00:18:48.740
that we can make where we
have a lot of predictive power

00:18:48.740 --> 00:18:50.128
by using the effective theory.

00:18:50.128 --> 00:18:51.920
And I want to talk a
little bit about that.

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:03.420
So you can look at
semi-leptonic decays.

00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:06.690
And there's two different types
of semi-leptonic decays that

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:08.430
you can look at--

00:19:08.430 --> 00:19:12.430
so-called exclusive decays
and inclusive decays.

00:19:12.430 --> 00:19:14.340
So exclusive is
making transitions

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:17.580
between the meson
states and inclusive

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:22.710
is making a transition where you
allow any charm state, not just

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:24.750
the lowest order
ground state charm,

00:19:24.750 --> 00:19:28.530
but you could have in
this state here, XE, you

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:32.710
could have a D pi or a D star
pi pi or other things like that.

00:19:32.710 --> 00:19:37.300
So it doesn't even have to
be a single hadron state.

00:19:37.300 --> 00:19:39.600
So exclusive refers to
a particular channel.

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:43.350
Inclusive refers to
some overall channels.

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:46.360
So the theory in these
two is quite different.

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:51.960
In this one, you would have
form factors for the current

00:19:51.960 --> 00:19:53.490
between the states.

00:19:53.490 --> 00:19:56.250
And I already mentioned to
you that heavy quark symmetry

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:57.810
reduces the number
of form factors.

00:19:57.810 --> 00:20:00.210
You get this single
Isgur-Wise function.

00:20:00.210 --> 00:20:06.270
And so heavy quark symmetry
is very powerful here.

00:20:06.270 --> 00:20:11.760
And you can actually also work
out 1 over MQ corrections.

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:13.240
And people have done that.

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:15.547
And it turns out
there aren't any.

00:20:15.547 --> 00:20:18.270
So there's something called
Luke's theorem, which actually

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:20.160
was a result derived,
I think, when

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:24.390
Luke was a graduate student that
proved there was no 1 over m Q

00:20:24.390 --> 00:20:26.400
corrections here.

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:28.470
And then you can work
out alpha s corrections.

00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:31.530
And so this kind of--
you can just keep going.

00:20:31.530 --> 00:20:34.350
People have worked out 1
over m Q squared corrections.

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:36.360
And this kind of
formalism is used

00:20:36.360 --> 00:20:41.010
to measure V c b because
these decay rates would depend

00:20:41.010 --> 00:20:43.170
on V c b, and that's
kind of what you're

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:45.180
after if you're doing this.

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:47.160
So you'd like to
parameterize and figure out

00:20:47.160 --> 00:20:49.230
the hadronic physics
as much as possible,

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:52.110
and aid the experiments
in getting V c b,

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:54.480
and exactly this
framework is used.

00:20:54.480 --> 00:20:56.790
People nowadays-- what
they do is, the 1 over m Q

00:20:56.790 --> 00:20:59.950
squared corrections need to
be computed on the lattice.

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:02.195
So lattice QCD computes
those corrections.

00:21:02.195 --> 00:21:03.570
The perturbative
corrections need

00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:06.460
to be computed by
continuum people like me,

00:21:06.460 --> 00:21:07.793
so those are computed.

00:21:07.793 --> 00:21:09.210
And they put these
things together

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:13.260
to get V c b from these decays.

00:21:13.260 --> 00:21:16.500
You could also do it
with this inclusive guy.

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:24.210
And here it's more interesting
because you can basically do

00:21:24.210 --> 00:21:27.337
everything with pen and paper.

00:21:27.337 --> 00:21:29.670
So here, you can use an
Operator Product Expansion, OPE.

00:21:34.770 --> 00:21:39.780
And actually, HQET constrains
the form of the operator

00:21:39.780 --> 00:21:41.330
product expansion, as well.

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:59.110
And indeed, when you work out
the leading power corrections,

00:21:59.110 --> 00:22:03.520
they turn out to not enter
until two orders down.

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:06.370
So again, you're protected
from first-order corrections,

00:22:06.370 --> 00:22:11.380
so you just get corrections that
occur at 1 over m Q squared.

00:22:11.380 --> 00:22:15.403
And furthermore, they depend
only on the two parameters

00:22:15.403 --> 00:22:16.195
we already defined.

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:23.830
So it's not like you even get
any new nonperturbative matrix

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:24.330
comments.

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:26.288
You just get the two we
were talking over here,

00:22:26.288 --> 00:22:28.180
were the masses.

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:28.680
OK?

00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:30.497
So there's perturbation
corrections,

00:22:30.497 --> 00:22:32.580
and there's power corrections,
but you're actually

00:22:32.580 --> 00:22:34.080
not even getting
any new information

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:38.230
relative to the masses,
any new matrix elements.

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:42.180
OK?

00:22:42.180 --> 00:22:44.100
So we'll talk a little bit
more about this second one

00:22:44.100 --> 00:22:44.642
with the OPE.

00:22:54.260 --> 00:22:56.060
There's a lot of
work that's gone

00:22:56.060 --> 00:22:58.850
into this one, both
from the theory side,

00:22:58.850 --> 00:23:00.397
as well as from experiment.

00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:08.060
So when you think about
the decay rate for this B

00:23:08.060 --> 00:23:11.780
to X sub c l nu bar, it's a
doubly differential decay rate

00:23:11.780 --> 00:23:17.540
in Q squared over the lepton
pair, so that's Q mu, E l--

00:23:17.540 --> 00:23:19.520
because you can pick it
as a second variable--

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:21.260
and then you don't know
the mass of the state

00:23:21.260 --> 00:23:23.130
X sub c because it could
be different things.

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:24.650
It could be a D. It
could be a D star.

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:25.442
It could be a D pi.

00:23:32.750 --> 00:23:34.798
So that's another variable.

00:23:34.798 --> 00:23:36.590
So you have a triply
differential spectrum,

00:23:36.590 --> 00:23:40.223
and you can compute it with
an operator product expansion.

00:23:49.638 --> 00:23:51.930
I'm not going to go through
the details of carrying out

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:54.180
the operator product expansion.

00:23:54.180 --> 00:23:56.555
If you want to do
reading about that,

00:23:56.555 --> 00:23:57.930
there's some
supplemental reading

00:23:57.930 --> 00:23:59.712
that I haven't
assigned to you where

00:23:59.712 --> 00:24:01.170
you can read about
that in the book

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:03.990
Heavy Quark Physics
by Manohar and Wise.

00:24:08.730 --> 00:24:13.470
So for our purposes here, let's
think of what operator product

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:15.817
expansion means.

00:24:15.817 --> 00:24:17.400
It is simply that
we want to carry out

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:35.370
an expansion in
lambda QCD over m Q.

00:24:35.370 --> 00:24:38.130
And if you go into
the details, there's

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:39.630
an important role
played by the fact

00:24:39.630 --> 00:24:41.130
that you're summing
over all states,

00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:43.110
and that's allowing
you to connect

00:24:43.110 --> 00:24:46.350
the partonic calculations to
the hadronic calculations,

00:24:46.350 --> 00:24:48.740
basically by probability
conservation,

00:24:48.740 --> 00:24:52.380
but I'm not going to
go so much into that.

00:24:52.380 --> 00:24:56.370
So when you do this
operator product expansion,

00:24:56.370 --> 00:24:58.470
you can think of it
in terms of diagrams.

00:24:58.470 --> 00:25:02.100
And usually, you draw these
diagrams as forward diagrams.

00:25:02.100 --> 00:25:04.380
So here's kind of the
matrix elements squared.

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:08.970
Here is the final state.

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:16.543
There's the b quark going in
and another b quark going out,

00:25:16.543 --> 00:25:18.210
so that's like a
matrix element squared.

00:25:22.194 --> 00:25:24.698
The amplitude squared.

00:25:24.698 --> 00:25:26.990
And you think about doing an
operator product expansion

00:25:26.990 --> 00:25:27.490
for that.

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:32.420
And you match onto operators
in the effective theory.

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:41.790
Just to give you a schematic
structure for those operators.

00:25:52.770 --> 00:25:55.860
So there's a
leading-order operator.

00:25:55.860 --> 00:25:57.660
There's a
subleading-order operator

00:25:57.660 --> 00:26:00.000
that has an extra
covariant derivative in it.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:01.560
That's kind of
what you would do.

00:26:01.560 --> 00:26:03.780
And then you have
Wilson coefficients.

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:07.600
The leading-order operator
here is just b bar b.

00:26:07.600 --> 00:26:09.540
That's what it turns out to be.

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:12.540
This operator here
would look familiar

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:16.360
because it's D
transverse squared,

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:18.040
so that's like our
lambda 1 operator,

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:20.520
and that's where the lambda
1's are going to come from.

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:22.187
And then there would
be a lambda 2 term,

00:26:22.187 --> 00:26:24.770
and I just didn't write it.

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:26.852
So there's a magnetic
guy here, too.

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:36.910
So when you look at the
leading-order operator,

00:26:36.910 --> 00:26:40.570
b bar b, that counts the
number of b quarks, OK?

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:42.930
That's just a number operator.

00:26:42.930 --> 00:26:47.680
So to all orders in perturbation
theory, b bar b is 1.

00:26:50.420 --> 00:26:50.920
Yeah?

00:26:53.990 --> 00:26:56.960
AUDIENCE: How do you cut these--

00:26:56.960 --> 00:26:58.567
like, you're
actually calculating

00:26:58.567 --> 00:26:59.900
[? B to A, right? ?] [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:00.733
IAIN STEWART: Right.

00:27:00.733 --> 00:27:02.660
So you should think
of actually looking--

00:27:02.660 --> 00:27:04.920
so this is a charm quark.

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:07.160
And so you would write
down that propagator,

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:09.770
and then you have a large
injection of momentum

00:27:09.770 --> 00:27:11.600
from the b quark, right?

00:27:11.600 --> 00:27:14.780
Use momentum conservation
and expand the propagator.

00:27:14.780 --> 00:27:16.700
Thinking about the
propagator, if you like,

00:27:16.700 --> 00:27:21.410
thinking about this
guy here having--

00:27:21.410 --> 00:27:27.110
so you could write this guy's
momentum as m b v plus k,

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:27.650
all right?

00:27:27.650 --> 00:27:30.177
And you would expand in k.

00:27:30.177 --> 00:27:32.510
So at first order, you just
drop all the k's, and that's

00:27:32.510 --> 00:27:34.520
basically giving you this term.

00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:36.230
At second order,
you'd keep the k's,

00:27:36.230 --> 00:27:37.970
so the k squared
would be identified

00:27:37.970 --> 00:27:40.130
with this D t squared.

00:27:40.130 --> 00:27:43.880
AUDIENCE: Right, but how do you
cut the effective [INAUDIBLE]??

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:46.850
IAIN STEWART: The effective
theory diagram, it's

00:27:46.850 --> 00:27:48.830
already been cut, if you like.

00:27:48.830 --> 00:27:51.260
So this is just a real
thing, and I've already

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:53.190
taken the imaginary part.

00:27:53.190 --> 00:27:55.760
So this is all real.

00:27:55.760 --> 00:27:58.140
There's no cut to make
in the effective theory.

00:27:58.140 --> 00:27:59.970
The thing I'm
integrating out here--

00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:01.280
so this is a good comment.

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:04.580
The thing I'm integrating out
here is hard and off-shell.

00:28:04.580 --> 00:28:06.680
So when I go over to
the effective theory

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:12.080
and I get rid of the off-shell
stuff, I have a real part here.

00:28:12.080 --> 00:28:16.210
There's nothing to cut
in the effective theory.

00:28:16.210 --> 00:28:17.657
Sometimes, as you
know, there are

00:28:17.657 --> 00:28:19.240
things to cut in the
effective theory,

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:21.640
but here there's nothing
to cut on this side.

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:33.790
OK, so this is one tall order.

00:28:33.790 --> 00:28:35.770
So that actually means
that we don't even

00:28:35.770 --> 00:28:37.750
have a nontrivial
matrix element here.

00:28:37.750 --> 00:28:39.790
We just have a
Wilson coefficient.

00:28:39.790 --> 00:28:44.640
So everything in the first-order
term is completely calculable.

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:54.540
No nonperturbative parameter
because of symmetry.

00:28:54.540 --> 00:28:56.997
And this guy here is
the power correction.

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:06.630
And if you look at what
the Wilson coefficient is--

00:29:06.630 --> 00:29:08.465
so it's a function of alpha s.

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:14.440
You could think of it
like this, if you want.

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:28.090
And all the kinematic variables,
like kinematic variables

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:30.070
like these guys--

00:29:30.070 --> 00:29:41.890
and it is equal to the free b
quark decay, including the loop

00:29:41.890 --> 00:29:43.750
corrections, of course.

00:29:43.750 --> 00:29:45.490
So not only the
tree-level result,

00:29:45.490 --> 00:29:50.170
but adding loop corrections
to the right-hand side here.

00:29:50.170 --> 00:29:52.960
If you add the loop
corrections and you

00:29:52.960 --> 00:29:58.300
drop all the k squared's, then
you get just the free b quark

00:29:58.300 --> 00:30:00.923
decay, no nonperturbative
matrix elements,

00:30:00.923 --> 00:30:03.340
so you can just calculate that
first term, order by order.

00:30:03.340 --> 00:30:05.380
Just doing a
[? partonic ?] calculation

00:30:05.380 --> 00:30:07.840
gives you the right thing
to describe this decay.

00:30:10.670 --> 00:30:13.295
And the OPE is telling
you that that formally

00:30:13.295 --> 00:30:14.420
is exactly the right thing.

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:16.070
Even if you just
started to do it,

00:30:16.070 --> 00:30:19.130
it's actually technically
the right thing to do here.

00:30:19.130 --> 00:30:23.360
It wouldn't be the right thing
to do for the exclusive decays,

00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:26.510
but it is the right thing to
do here for the inclusive.

00:30:37.280 --> 00:30:40.130
So what is the range of
validity of this sort of--

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:42.740
is there any restrictions on
these kinematic variables?

00:30:42.740 --> 00:30:44.000
And there is.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:46.505
We're treating the kinematic
variables as if they're hard.

00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:52.770
And that means
basically that we're

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:55.740
thinking that they scale like
powers of the heavy quark mass.

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:02.540
So there can be
regions of phase space

00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:04.820
where that wouldn't
be true, but as long

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:10.210
as we stay away from
those corners, edges, then

00:31:10.210 --> 00:31:11.130
what I said is right.

00:31:15.790 --> 00:31:18.980
And it's a little more
powerful than that.

00:31:18.980 --> 00:31:22.690
So stay away from edges.

00:31:27.340 --> 00:31:31.180
Or there's another way
of thinking about it,

00:31:31.180 --> 00:31:32.890
and that is that you
can integrate over

00:31:32.890 --> 00:31:37.045
regions of the Dalitz plane
for the phase-space variables.

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:46.670
That includes all the
way up to the edges.

00:31:46.670 --> 00:31:53.770
And as long as the size
of your integration region

00:31:53.770 --> 00:31:57.600
is order m Q, then
you're also fine.

00:31:57.600 --> 00:32:00.540
So think of, like,
something with,

00:32:00.540 --> 00:32:05.777
like, m B squared up here,
d m x squared, for example.

00:32:05.777 --> 00:32:08.110
And you can-- it doesn't have
to be exactly m B squared.

00:32:08.110 --> 00:32:10.652
It could be m B squared over 2,
m B squared over 4, something

00:32:10.652 --> 00:32:12.880
that you're counting
as order m B squared.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:16.410
And again, you would be
fine with doing this type

00:32:16.410 --> 00:32:20.207
of operator product expansion.

00:32:20.207 --> 00:32:22.040
So what happens is, if
you restrict yourself

00:32:22.040 --> 00:32:24.347
to be close to the
edges, then restricting

00:32:24.347 --> 00:32:26.180
yourself to be close
to the edges introduces

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:27.952
new scales in the problem.

00:32:27.952 --> 00:32:29.660
And if there's new
scales in the problem,

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:32.160
just having a power counting
that separates out lambda, QCD,

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:34.070
and m B would not be enough.

00:32:34.070 --> 00:32:37.670
You would have to
do more detail.

00:32:37.670 --> 00:32:39.860
And there is actually
some interesting things

00:32:39.860 --> 00:32:41.737
that happen there,
and we probably

00:32:41.737 --> 00:32:43.820
will talk about at least
one example later on when

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:47.840
we talk about [? SCT. ?]

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:50.870
OK, so I already said it,
that there's a nontrivial fact

00:32:50.870 --> 00:32:53.570
happening at NLO.

00:32:53.570 --> 00:32:56.840
Well, I already
implied that there's

