00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:35.760
to tell you about renormalons.

00:37:35.760 --> 00:37:37.260
Actually, renormalons
have something

00:37:37.260 --> 00:37:38.640
to do with power
correction, so it's not

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:40.820
disconnected from what
we've been talking about.

00:37:48.160 --> 00:37:49.560
So what are the ideas here?

00:38:02.523 --> 00:38:04.940
So we've already seen in our
discussion of renormalization

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:07.340
that there is a
freedom in defining

00:38:07.340 --> 00:38:09.120
the perturbative series.

00:38:09.120 --> 00:38:11.570
And we kind of focused
on the m s bar scheme

00:38:11.570 --> 00:38:12.740
as being the simplest thing.

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:19.603
But I told you about some
subtleties with m s bar,

00:38:19.603 --> 00:38:21.020
and now we're going
to address one

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:24.170
of them that's related to
this thing called renormalons.

00:38:36.590 --> 00:38:41.090
So we have some freedom, if you
like, in adjusting the cutoffs.

00:38:41.090 --> 00:38:42.712
And we had this
cutoff, mu, and it

00:38:42.712 --> 00:38:44.420
was dividing up what
was perturbative and

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:46.695
nonperturbative in m s bar.

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:51.863
But we could have
done something else.

00:38:51.863 --> 00:38:53.780
We could have used a
different type of cutoff.

00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:55.987
We could have used
a Wilsonian cutoff,

00:38:55.987 --> 00:38:58.070
and that would have divided
up things a little bit

00:38:58.070 --> 00:38:59.490
differently.

00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:01.940
And you should ask the
question, are any possible way

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:03.803
of dividing things
up equivalent?

00:39:07.430 --> 00:39:10.790
We've already saw when we
were doing calculations

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:14.300
that, for the logarithms,
they were equivalent.

00:39:14.300 --> 00:39:19.790
But it turns out
that, if you don't--

00:39:19.790 --> 00:39:23.270
that the powers, sort
of the power separation

00:39:23.270 --> 00:39:27.080
of power divergences can
actually have an impact.

00:39:31.470 --> 00:39:33.830
And that's related to
what renormalons are.

00:39:41.580 --> 00:39:44.780
And m s bar and
dim reg basically

00:39:44.780 --> 00:39:46.800
avoids thinking about
power corrections.

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:48.710
You just set them to zero.

00:39:48.710 --> 00:39:51.650
And so what can
happen is, in m s bar,

00:39:51.650 --> 00:39:54.500
your matrix elements are
having a little bit too much UV

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:56.690
physics, and your Wilson
coefficients are actually

00:39:56.690 --> 00:39:57.753
sensitive to the IR.

00:39:57.753 --> 00:39:59.420
They're not sensitive--
you don't really

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:01.087
see it when you look
at the coefficient.

00:40:01.087 --> 00:40:03.230
You just see a number,
and it looks pretty good,

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:05.455
but there's actually
an asymptotic structure

00:40:05.455 --> 00:40:06.830
to those Wilson
coefficients that

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.050
comes from higher orders
of perturbation theory.

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:10.590
There's things hiding there.

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:12.980
That's what this discussion
is going to be about.

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:29.490
So if you do actually
not make a good choice,

00:40:29.490 --> 00:40:31.080
then it can be
the case that when

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:34.470
you go to higher orders in
the perturbative expansion,

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:36.210
you get lousy convergence.

00:40:40.830 --> 00:40:44.280
And that goes
hand-in-hand, actually,

00:40:44.280 --> 00:40:50.550
with kind of another thing,
which is harder to visualize,

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:54.180
but I'll explain it.

00:40:54.180 --> 00:40:56.640
And that is that you
have trouble extracting

00:40:56.640 --> 00:40:58.476
the nonperturbative parameters.

00:41:15.168 --> 00:41:16.960
And the reason that
you're having trouble--

00:41:16.960 --> 00:41:19.000
so you could think about
doing some calculation

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:20.710
like that OPE over there.

00:41:20.710 --> 00:41:23.650
And you extract a value for
lambda 1 from all your fits

00:41:23.650 --> 00:41:25.652
to all these moments I
was describing to you.

00:41:25.652 --> 00:41:27.610
And then you go to one
higher order in alpha s,

00:41:27.610 --> 00:41:29.420
and you extract another
value, and all of a sudden,

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:30.795
this guy changes
by a factor of 2

00:41:30.795 --> 00:41:33.050
and you wonder what's going on.

00:41:33.050 --> 00:41:35.170
And you wonder, well,
what's nature telling you

00:41:35.170 --> 00:41:37.180
about the kinetic
energy if I change

00:41:37.180 --> 00:41:39.638
the order of my perturbation
theory and all of a sudden I'm

00:41:39.638 --> 00:41:43.060
extracting a factor of 2
different value for that matrix

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:44.170
element.

00:41:44.170 --> 00:41:47.150
And that's related actually
to this poor convergence.

00:41:47.150 --> 00:41:48.520
These things go hand in hand.

00:41:48.520 --> 00:41:51.010
If there's pure
convergence in the series,

00:41:51.010 --> 00:41:54.940
then when you extract
matrix elements

00:41:54.940 --> 00:41:56.722
you can get different values.

00:41:56.722 --> 00:41:58.180
Phenomenologically,
you can imagine

00:41:58.180 --> 00:42:00.790
how that would be related, but
it's physically related, too.

00:42:00.790 --> 00:42:03.730
It has to do with the fact that
there's a poor convergence here

00:42:03.730 --> 00:42:05.740
because you haven't
divided up the IR physics

00:42:05.740 --> 00:42:07.820
and the UV physics
fully correctly,

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:09.898
and that's reflected
in this inability

00:42:09.898 --> 00:42:11.815
to extract these guys
in a convergent fashion.

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:18.700
And we can actually quantify
that using something

00:42:18.700 --> 00:42:22.670
called renormalon techniques.

00:42:22.670 --> 00:42:30.010
So one way of saying it is
that, if you make a poor choice,

00:42:30.010 --> 00:42:32.050
you're plagued by something
called renormalons,

00:42:32.050 --> 00:42:34.467
so they're actually something
bad and you don't want them.

00:42:47.932 --> 00:43:02.510
So what goes wrong is that the
short distance of coefficients

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:14.390
have hidden power law
sensitivity to the IR.

00:43:14.390 --> 00:43:16.880
You wanted these
to be UV things,

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:19.520
but they are
sensitive to the IR.

00:43:19.520 --> 00:43:22.940
And it comes in dimensional
regularization in the powers.

00:43:22.940 --> 00:43:26.030
We've been very careful about
separating out logarithms,

00:43:26.030 --> 00:43:28.190
but we weren't as
careful about powers,

00:43:28.190 --> 00:43:33.860
and it comes back to haunt
us if we look carefully

00:43:33.860 --> 00:43:34.490
at the theory.

00:43:40.970 --> 00:43:44.040
And there's a
corresponding sensitivity

00:43:44.040 --> 00:43:48.020
to the UV in the
matrix elements.

00:43:48.020 --> 00:43:49.520
So let me give you
an example that's

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:51.620
not working through
formalism, but just numerics.

00:43:55.550 --> 00:44:01.040
So let's look at b to u
e bar nu at lowest order.

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:04.460
The up quark is massless.

00:44:04.460 --> 00:44:07.522
And we'll think
about this-- like we

00:44:07.522 --> 00:44:09.230
were talking about
for the OPE for charm,

00:44:09.230 --> 00:44:11.772
we'll think about it inclusively
so that we can actually just

00:44:11.772 --> 00:44:13.615
look at this and it
makes physical sense.

00:44:13.615 --> 00:44:15.740
The same thing that I told
you about the charm case

00:44:15.740 --> 00:44:17.240
applies for the up quark case.

00:44:17.240 --> 00:44:19.790
The lowest-order prediction
is just calculate this guy

00:44:19.790 --> 00:44:21.470
and include loop corrections.

00:44:21.470 --> 00:44:23.870
The leading power
prediction is the same story

00:44:23.870 --> 00:44:25.730
as for the charm.

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:28.130
So that means that
physically it's

00:44:28.130 --> 00:44:31.490
relevant to think
about this decay rate.

00:44:31.490 --> 00:44:34.580
So what does it look like?

00:44:34.580 --> 00:44:37.220
There's some G Fermi.

