00:45:37.310 --> 00:45:41.090
So you have some choice here
for how you define the b quark

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:43.370
mass, OK?

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:46.820
You could use the pole mass,
pole in the b quark propagator.

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:48.650
Or you could use
the m s bar mass.

00:45:48.650 --> 00:45:50.660
Or you could use some
other definition.

00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:53.040
And it's raised
to the 5th power.

00:45:53.040 --> 00:45:55.040
So whatever definition
you pick, it

00:45:55.040 --> 00:45:57.243
can be pretty sensitive to that.

00:45:57.243 --> 00:45:58.910
So let me tell you
what the results look

00:45:58.910 --> 00:46:04.142
like in three different
schemes for that mass.

00:46:04.142 --> 00:46:06.530
So let's first do
the pole scheme.

00:46:06.530 --> 00:46:09.540
This is the same.

00:46:09.540 --> 00:46:12.155
We have m b pole
to the 5th power,

00:46:12.155 --> 00:46:14.030
and then we'd write out
what the series looks

00:46:14.030 --> 00:46:15.386
like in that scheme.

00:46:23.427 --> 00:46:25.010
You look like you're
doing pretty good

00:46:25.010 --> 00:46:26.010
when you're at one loop.

00:46:26.010 --> 00:46:27.555
You went down by a factor of 5.

00:46:27.555 --> 00:46:29.180
But then you go into
two loops, and you

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:31.040
find that your
correction at two loops

00:46:31.040 --> 00:46:33.540
