00:49:50.327 --> 00:49:52.660
We could also think about
switching from the pole scheme

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:56.680
to this m b 1S scheme.

00:49:56.680 --> 00:49:57.805
We have a different series.

00:50:02.920 --> 00:50:04.963
It still doesn't
look very convergent.

00:50:10.280 --> 00:50:12.170
The numbers look small, but--

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:14.040
this is supposed to be a 6--

00:50:14.040 --> 00:50:16.040
but this number here is
bigger than that number.

00:50:18.770 --> 00:50:21.550
So that when I stick this
series and combine it together

00:50:21.550 --> 00:50:24.130
with this series
for the pole mass,

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:27.430
then I get that series
at the top of the board.

00:50:27.430 --> 00:50:30.160
And the problem is
not in the m b 1S.

00:50:30.160 --> 00:50:32.073
The problem is in the m b pole.

00:50:32.073 --> 00:50:33.490
And the problem
in the m b pole is

00:50:33.490 --> 00:50:35.282
being reflected in this
series that relates

00:50:35.282 --> 00:50:38.781
them and its poor convergence.

00:50:38.781 --> 00:50:40.948
AUDIENCE: Can you explain
[? what ?] [? m ?] [? b ?]

00:50:40.948 --> 00:50:43.156
[? bar ?] [? being ?]
[? perturbative ?] [? means? ?]

00:50:43.156 --> 00:50:44.740
IAIN STEWART: Yeah,
so you calculate--

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:48.520
so you can think of calculating
the Coulomb potential between b

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:53.020
and b bar, and that will
give you alpha s corrections

00:50:53.020 --> 00:50:54.610
to just the mass.

00:50:54.610 --> 00:50:57.700
So you have 2 m b plus Coulomb
potential plus, you know,

00:50:57.700 --> 00:50:59.010
radiative corrections to that.

00:50:59.010 --> 00:51:01.750
And you keep dressing it
up and just perturbatively

00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:06.910
calculate as if it was a
Coulomb problem, a QED problem,

00:51:06.910 --> 00:51:11.942
the mass of the b b bar state,
and then you divide by 2.

00:51:11.942 --> 00:51:15.295
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:15.295 --> 00:51:16.270
IAIN STEWART: Yeah

00:51:16.270 --> 00:51:18.060
AUDIENCE: But you just pretend?

00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:20.102
IAIN STEWART: There's
nonperturbative corrections

00:51:20.102 --> 00:51:23.960
to it, but what we're extracting
from it is the series.

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:24.930
OK?

00:51:24.930 --> 00:51:26.990
I'll explain more why
it's going to work,

00:51:26.990 --> 00:51:31.330
why this is, like, a reasonable
choice, and we'll come to that.

00:51:31.330 --> 00:51:37.270
OK, so the lesson here is simply
that the choice of mass scheme

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:41.680
has a big impact on the
perturbative series.

00:51:47.550 --> 00:51:50.075
And we haven't yet figured
out why some things work

00:51:50.075 --> 00:51:51.700
and why some things
don't, but we will.

00:51:56.800 --> 00:51:58.867
It's absolutely crucial
to use the right one.

00:51:58.867 --> 00:52:00.700
Otherwise, the predictions
will not be good.

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:05.730
Well, physically,
we can actually

00:52:05.730 --> 00:52:09.250
argue right away why m
b pole is not so good.

00:52:12.928 --> 00:52:14.970
And that's because,
physically, there is no pole.

00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:20.670
There's no pole in
the quark propagator.

00:52:29.790 --> 00:52:32.026
And that is because
of confinement.

00:52:42.450 --> 00:52:44.750
So we use this notion of
pole and a quark propagator

00:52:44.750 --> 00:52:46.620
when we're doing
perturbation theory.

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:50.330
But nonperturbatively, it's
not a well-defined notion,

00:52:50.330 --> 00:52:52.340
or at least there doesn't
really exist poles

00:52:52.340 --> 00:52:53.825
in quark propagators.

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:02.460
So it's only perturbatively
a good notion.

00:53:24.240 --> 00:53:28.320
So I'll say it's only
perturbatively meaningful.

00:53:28.320 --> 00:53:39.290
And in reality, it's ambiguous,
it's an ambiguous notion.

00:53:39.290 --> 00:53:41.690
And you can think that the
amount by which it's ambiguous

00:53:41.690 --> 00:53:43.460
is related to
hadronization, which

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:47.090
is set by the scale lambda QCD.

00:53:47.090 --> 00:53:48.890
So there's an
ambiguity in what you

00:53:48.890 --> 00:53:54.230
mean by a pole mass physically
due to nonperturbative effects.

00:53:54.230 --> 00:53:56.960
Now, when we set up HQET,
we actually used m pole.

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:10.800
So we're using a questionable
physical parameter.

00:54:10.800 --> 00:54:15.230
So when we did these
phase redefinitions,

00:54:15.230 --> 00:54:18.050
we were actually using
the pole mass scheme

00:54:18.050 --> 00:54:20.249
because we were expanding
about mass shell.

00:54:33.960 --> 00:54:36.580
So if you were to
do other things,

00:54:36.580 --> 00:54:40.230
you can think about
getting to other choices

00:54:40.230 --> 00:54:42.230
and implementing
them in the HQET.

00:54:45.060 --> 00:54:48.790
No problem with doing that.

00:54:48.790 --> 00:54:54.240
But there does exist
another operator

00:54:54.240 --> 00:54:59.470
that we sort of dropped without
thinking too hard about it.

00:54:59.470 --> 00:55:02.580
So if we switch to using
a different mass scheme,

00:55:02.580 --> 00:55:04.860
there's some delta
m, which you can

00:55:04.860 --> 00:55:10.560
think of as a series in
alpha s, which we wrote

00:55:10.560 --> 00:55:12.150
on the board a moment ago.

00:55:17.310 --> 00:55:20.370
And where that delta
m would show up

00:55:20.370 --> 00:55:25.410
is that you would have kind of
an L delta m operator, which

00:55:25.410 --> 00:55:32.580
would just be exactly delta
m, and then Q v bar Q v.

00:55:32.580 --> 00:55:35.550
That would be left over
when we cancel the masses

00:55:35.550 --> 00:55:37.670
in the Lagrangian, if you like.

00:55:37.670 --> 00:55:39.170
That's one way of
thinking about it.

00:55:44.040 --> 00:55:47.810
So we have an extra term
in the Lagrangian in HQET.

00:55:47.810 --> 00:55:50.360
And now you can ask, well,
if we have an extra term,

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:52.940
we'd better worry
about power counting.

00:55:52.940 --> 00:55:54.440
And it turns out
that the way we can

00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:56.630
understand why m s
bar wasn't working

00:55:56.630 --> 00:55:57.890
is related to power counting.

00:56:02.770 --> 00:56:08.260
So in m s bar, if you
look at what delta m is,

00:56:08.260 --> 00:56:13.120
delta m is m bar
itself times alpha.

00:56:13.120 --> 00:56:15.100
But by power counting,
you don't want

00:56:15.100 --> 00:56:17.860
something that's growing
with m b in the Lagrangian.

00:56:21.050 --> 00:56:25.395
m b is suppressed by alpha,
but it's alpha at m b that is

00:56:25.395 --> 00:56:27.020
providing [? some ?]
[? suppression, ?]

00:56:27.020 --> 00:56:29.840
but that's only 0.2, and
that's actually just not enough

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:32.600
suppression to get rid
of the big m b here.

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:35.955
You don't get--
you go from 5 GV--

00:56:35.955 --> 00:56:37.580
you know, there's
some number in front.

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:40.280
Maybe you get down
to 1 and 1/2, 2 GV,

00:56:40.280 --> 00:56:43.130
but you're not getting down
to a small enough value.

00:56:46.500 --> 00:56:51.830
So parametrically, this is just
not good, both parametrically,

00:56:51.830 --> 00:56:57.810
because it grows with m b,
and numerically it's too big.

00:57:01.160 --> 00:57:03.470
It's not order lambda
QCD, which would be OK.

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:12.420
So parametrically
and numerically,

00:57:12.420 --> 00:57:20.040
delta m is just too big for
HQET power counting in this m

00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:20.700
s bar scheme.

00:57:24.268 --> 00:57:27.930
You'd include an operator
that effectively is on average

00:57:27.930 --> 00:57:32.720
larger and more important than
your kinetic term because the v

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:36.930
dot D operator-- v dot D is
counting like lambda QCD,

00:57:36.930 --> 00:57:39.690
and it had v dot D with two Q's.

00:57:39.690 --> 00:57:42.360
Now you have something delta
m with two Q's, and if it's

00:57:42.360 --> 00:57:44.790
on average larger,
then you're messed up.

00:57:51.640 --> 00:57:54.480
So that's why actually
physically the m b bar

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:55.440
is not a good choice.

00:57:55.440 --> 00:57:58.200
You can think about it from the
effective theory from that way.

00:57:58.200 --> 00:58:01.213
m b bar is actually
a mass that's--

00:58:01.213 --> 00:58:02.880
you're supposed to
think of it as a mass

00:58:02.880 --> 00:58:04.422
that you use for
high-energy physics,

00:58:04.422 --> 00:58:07.740
for physics really high energy,
above the b quark mass scale.

00:58:07.740 --> 00:58:10.210
Then it's a good parameter.

00:58:10.210 --> 00:58:13.510
We're now doing physics
below the b quark mass scale,

00:58:13.510 --> 00:58:15.880
and this is just
one way of seeing

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:18.490
why it's not such a
good parameter there,

00:58:18.490 --> 00:58:20.740
because the perturbative
corrections are just too big.

00:58:23.960 --> 00:58:26.494
So what about this 1S mass?

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:36.370
So here, it turns out that
if you calculate delta m,

00:58:36.370 --> 00:58:37.320
you get--

00:58:37.320 --> 00:58:39.820
in the same way that you think
about corrections to hydrogen

00:58:39.820 --> 00:58:44.320
being order alpha squared,
you get m b 1s alpha squared.

00:58:44.320 --> 00:58:47.290
And numerically,
that's small enough

00:58:47.290 --> 00:58:49.840
when you put the coefficient in.

00:58:49.840 --> 00:58:54.340
So it still doesn't make us
feel very good because it grows

00:58:54.340 --> 00:58:56.655
with m b, but if I just
care about numerics

00:58:56.655 --> 00:58:58.030
and I'm doing b
quark physics, it

00:58:58.030 --> 00:59:01.870
works because the alpha
squared is enough suppression

00:59:01.870 --> 00:59:03.820
that this is a good
mass scheme, and that's

00:59:03.820 --> 00:59:06.520
why the perturbation theory
treating as order lambda

00:59:06.520 --> 00:59:11.050
QCD numerically, if
not parametically.

00:59:14.830 --> 00:59:15.580
Is OK.

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:22.330
Now, if that doesn't
sit pretty with you,

00:59:22.330 --> 00:59:25.008
you can do something
even more fancy,

00:59:25.008 --> 00:59:27.550
and we'll talk about one example
of more fancy a little later

00:59:27.550 --> 00:59:31.480
on, where you basically, instead
of having m show up there,

00:59:31.480 --> 00:59:36.132
you have some parameter
R, and you have something

00:59:36.132 --> 00:59:37.090
that you can just pick.

00:59:41.410 --> 00:59:43.000
And so you could
pick a scheme here

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:46.990
where R is of order
lambda QCD-- by however,

00:59:46.990 --> 00:59:52.600
maybe you pick it be 1 GV or
500 MeV or whatever you like.

00:59:52.600 --> 00:59:54.880
So you can make up a
scheme where this is true,

00:59:54.880 --> 00:59:58.330
and then both parametrically
and numerically you're OK.

00:59:58.330 --> 01:00:01.300
And these schemes also work
just as well as the 1S scheme.

01:00:04.740 --> 01:00:06.750
So we can get more
fancy and also satisfy

01:00:06.750 --> 01:00:10.290
our formal requirement.

01:00:10.290 --> 01:00:14.190
All right, so that's kind
of phenomenological numbers

01:00:14.190 --> 01:00:16.300
and a bit of physics.

01:00:16.300 --> 01:00:19.140
Let's come back to some
mathematics and talk about what

01:00:19.140 --> 01:00:20.985
renormalons are mathematically.

01:00:24.450 --> 01:00:26.418
Is there a mathematical
way of characterizing

01:00:26.418 --> 01:00:27.210
what's going wrong?

01:00:27.210 --> 01:00:29.730
What if I didn't think
about this physics?

01:00:29.730 --> 01:00:33.550
Could I do a calculation and see
that something's going wrong?

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:36.900
And the answer is yes.

01:00:36.900 --> 01:00:39.030
So first I have to
teach you a few things,

01:00:39.030 --> 01:00:43.500
if you don't know them
already, about the asymptotics

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:48.820
of perturbative series
in quantum field theory.

01:00:48.820 --> 01:00:52.335
And these are actually
not convergent series.

01:01:01.930 --> 01:01:05.580
So they are what are
called asymptotic series.

01:01:12.470 --> 01:01:16.020
So what's the definition
of an asymptotic series?

01:01:16.020 --> 01:01:22.310
So we say a function has
an asymmetric series, which

01:01:22.310 --> 01:01:24.170
I'll write as follows.

01:01:24.170 --> 01:01:26.000
Some coefficients.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:28.100
And we'll just call the
expansion parameter alpha.

01:01:28.100 --> 01:01:30.600
You can think of it as
alpha s, if you like,

01:01:30.600 --> 01:01:32.533
but this is just
math, so you don't

01:01:32.533 --> 01:01:34.700
have to think about it as
anything but the expansion

01:01:34.700 --> 01:01:35.720
parameter.

01:01:35.720 --> 01:01:39.860
And we say that a function
has an asymptotic series if

01:01:39.860 --> 01:01:43.820
and only if the
following is true.

01:01:43.820 --> 01:01:52.730
f of alpha minus the partial
sum up to some level n

01:01:52.730 --> 01:01:57.110
is less than kind of
the scaling that you

01:01:57.110 --> 01:02:04.610
would get from the next term in
the series, which is n plus 2,

01:02:04.610 --> 01:02:11.300
for some numbers K N plus 2.

01:02:14.660 --> 01:02:18.050
So that's actually a
quite different definition

01:02:18.050 --> 01:02:20.593
than what you would have
for a convergent series.

01:02:20.593 --> 01:02:22.010
For a convergence
areas, you would

01:02:22.010 --> 01:02:24.820
say that you could pick
any epsilon you like here.

01:02:24.820 --> 01:02:26.660
You could make the N
big enough that this

01:02:26.660 --> 01:02:28.730
would get close to that.

01:02:28.730 --> 01:02:31.520
Here, I'm just saying
that it's less than this

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:33.480
with some power of alpha.

01:02:33.480 --> 01:02:36.100
So imagine that I
pick alpha to be 0.1.

01:02:36.100 --> 01:02:40.130
The thing is that this K
here could still grow with N,

01:02:40.130 --> 01:02:42.470
and that actually will happen.

01:02:42.470 --> 01:02:43.970
So the truncation
area in some sense

01:02:43.970 --> 01:02:46.400
is not being bounded in
these asymptotic series.

01:02:50.620 --> 01:02:52.780
And perturbation theory
and quantum field theory

01:02:52.780 --> 01:02:54.370
is generically of
this structure,

01:02:54.370 --> 01:02:56.610
and I'll show you
some examples of that.

01:03:00.230 --> 01:03:02.378
It's asymptotic rather
than convergent.

01:03:10.360 --> 01:03:13.615
So when you do a
QFT calculation,

01:03:13.615 --> 01:03:19.810
a kind of typical result if
you work out some asymptotics

01:03:19.810 --> 01:03:23.080
is that you would have
these fn coefficients that

01:03:23.080 --> 01:03:28.720
are some power of a, and
then times an n factorial.

01:03:31.300 --> 01:03:34.510
And that's kind of how they're
scaling as n is getting large.

01:03:34.510 --> 01:03:37.930
You can think about the number
of diagrams as just growing,

01:03:37.930 --> 01:03:40.180
but even when diagrams
are not growing

01:03:40.180 --> 01:03:41.490
you can get these n factorials.

01:03:44.590 --> 01:03:49.630
So that means if you're
fixing alpha as some value

01:03:49.630 --> 01:03:53.710
of the parameter, and no
matter how small you take it,

01:03:53.710 --> 01:03:56.230
at some order in
perturbation theory,

01:03:56.230 --> 01:04:00.340
you're basically running out
of gas, and your truncation--

01:04:00.340 --> 01:04:02.890
you start to--

01:04:02.890 --> 01:04:08.810
your predictions start
to grow and diverge.

01:04:08.810 --> 01:04:11.050
So the corresponding
values of these K's,

01:04:11.050 --> 01:04:13.030
if you had these f's
that were of that form,

01:04:13.030 --> 01:04:15.700
would be that the K's
are basically growing

01:04:15.700 --> 01:04:18.770
in the same way.

01:04:18.770 --> 01:04:20.860
So you'd need larger and
larger numbers in order

01:04:20.860 --> 01:04:23.680
to satisfy the definition
of asymptotic over there,

01:04:23.680 --> 01:04:25.660
and having these large
numbers you're never

01:04:25.660 --> 01:04:29.320
able to satisfy convergent.

01:04:29.320 --> 01:04:32.830
So the series has zero
radius of convergence.

01:04:40.063 --> 01:04:41.980
And then you wonder, why
have we been teaching

01:04:41.980 --> 01:04:43.022
you quantum field theory?

01:04:43.022 --> 01:04:44.920
[CHUCKLES] That's true.

01:04:47.540 --> 01:04:48.400
So what do we know?

01:04:48.400 --> 01:04:50.440
Even though these
series are asymptotic,

01:04:50.440 --> 01:04:55.500
we can still make use of them.

01:04:55.500 --> 01:05:00.500
So typically what happens is
that the series will decrease.

01:05:00.500 --> 01:05:02.390
For a while, it'll look
like it's convergent,

01:05:02.390 --> 01:05:04.760
and then it'll start diverging.

01:05:04.760 --> 01:05:10.770
And you can characterize
where it starts to diverge.

01:05:10.770 --> 01:05:12.770
And I'm not going to go
through all the algebra,

01:05:12.770 --> 01:05:15.075
but I'll just tell
you some facts.

01:05:18.720 --> 01:05:20.220
And so you could
imagine that you're

01:05:20.220 --> 01:05:21.803
doing some perturbation
series, and it

01:05:21.803 --> 01:05:24.240
looks like it's going well.

01:05:24.240 --> 01:05:26.050
Things are converging.

01:05:26.050 --> 01:05:29.340
But then, [? some ?]
[? things ?] don't start to go

01:05:29.340 --> 01:05:30.520
so well.

01:05:30.520 --> 01:05:32.130
So think of what
I'm plotting here

01:05:32.130 --> 01:05:34.440
as the partial sum
of your perturbation

01:05:34.440 --> 01:05:40.180
theory at N-th order.

01:05:40.180 --> 01:05:43.860
I sum up all the connections up
to N, so it's like the series

01:05:43.860 --> 01:05:45.620
that I was writing over here.

01:05:45.620 --> 01:05:47.730
It's this thing.

01:05:47.730 --> 01:05:53.760
Now, in perturbative
QED, perturbative QCD,

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:57.150
we're never getting
more than a few terms.

01:05:57.150 --> 01:05:58.920
So you could say,
well, OK, maybe I

01:05:58.920 --> 01:06:00.840
don't care so much about this.

01:06:00.840 --> 01:06:02.460
And in QED, that's
actually the case.

01:06:02.460 --> 01:06:05.310
You don't really care
so much about that.

01:06:05.310 --> 01:06:07.020
But in QCD, actually,
the turnover

01:06:07.020 --> 01:06:10.538
happens already around
three loops, and so as soon

01:06:10.538 --> 01:06:13.080
as you start including two loop
corrections this is something

01:06:13.080 --> 01:06:14.038
you have to care about.

01:06:16.590 --> 01:06:18.720
Now, you can say, well,
the best thing I can do

01:06:18.720 --> 01:06:21.990
is stop doing perturbation
theory at some N star

01:06:21.990 --> 01:06:24.270
because that's kind of
where it looks the best.

01:06:24.270 --> 01:06:27.430
Like, I've gone toward
something in it.

01:06:27.430 --> 01:06:30.410
And that actually is
not such a bad thing.

01:06:30.410 --> 01:06:32.490
And it turns out you can
characterize actually

01:06:32.490 --> 01:06:35.160
the mistake you're
making by stopping there,

01:06:35.160 --> 01:06:37.050
and the mistake you're
making by stopping

01:06:37.050 --> 01:06:40.140
there is of the following form.

01:06:44.790 --> 01:06:51.670
So it's an exponential
in 1 over alpha.

01:06:55.690 --> 01:07:00.360
So you would never be able
to see kind of the correction

01:07:00.360 --> 01:07:03.420
that you'd need to get to
the correct value, which I'm

01:07:03.420 --> 01:07:06.690
imagining is on the axis
here, in perturbation theory

01:07:06.690 --> 01:07:09.450
because this doesn't have
a perturbative expansion.

01:07:09.450 --> 01:07:12.570
And I'll actually show you
that kind of the bad behavior

01:07:12.570 --> 01:07:15.990
here and this gap are
related to power corrections.

01:07:15.990 --> 01:07:18.390
And they're exactly
related to this connection

01:07:18.390 --> 01:07:21.180
that I was telling you between
perturbative corrections

01:07:21.180 --> 01:07:24.510
and large-order asymptotics
and power corrections.

01:07:24.510 --> 01:07:27.073
This type of
exponential is something

01:07:27.073 --> 01:07:28.740
that we can relate
to power corrections,

01:07:28.740 --> 01:07:31.830
and we'll see how that pans
out, although we might--

01:07:31.830 --> 01:07:35.110
probably won't get
there until next class.

01:07:35.110 --> 01:07:37.950
OK, so this is
kind of a prelude,

01:07:37.950 --> 01:07:40.230
and now we're going to
go into more detail.

01:07:40.230 --> 01:07:43.050
And it turns out, in order
to go into more detail here,

01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:46.050
that, much as you make
Fourier transforms

01:07:46.050 --> 01:07:48.240
to explore another
space, we're going

01:07:48.240 --> 01:07:51.045
to do a transform to
something called Borel space.

01:08:01.420 --> 01:08:03.940
So it turns out
that, when you have

01:08:03.940 --> 01:08:07.870
a divergent series or
an asymptotic series,

01:08:07.870 --> 01:08:10.930
there's still degrees
of divergence.

01:08:10.930 --> 01:08:12.940
And we can classify
how divergent

01:08:12.940 --> 01:08:16.479
it is by using something
called the Borel transform.

01:08:29.529 --> 01:08:30.340
Yeah?

01:08:30.340 --> 01:08:36.130
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] will the
series still be asymptotic?

01:08:36.130 --> 01:08:39.580
IAIN STEWART: So no, it's not.

01:08:39.580 --> 01:08:41.950
Yeah, so 1S mass--

01:08:41.950 --> 01:08:43.420
let's see.

01:08:43.420 --> 01:08:49.902
Yeah, it is still
asymptotic, but it's--

01:08:49.902 --> 01:08:51.819
in a way that I'll
describe once we understand

01:08:51.819 --> 01:08:55.960
what this Borel is,
it's much less divergent

01:08:55.960 --> 01:08:58.623
than the other series,
than the pole series.

01:08:58.623 --> 01:09:00.040
If you think about
the pole series

01:09:00.040 --> 01:09:04.479
as being degree-0 divergent,
then this is like a few orders

01:09:04.479 --> 01:09:06.880
down less divergent.

01:09:06.880 --> 01:09:10.976
So once we define less
divergent of a divergent series,

01:09:10.976 --> 01:09:12.809
then I'll be able to
make that more precise.

01:09:18.477 --> 01:09:20.560
It's a question of when
power corrections come in.

01:09:20.560 --> 01:09:22.420
And if you look at,
like-- so physically,

01:09:22.420 --> 01:09:26.800
the 1S mass is a physical
thing for an epsilon state.

01:09:26.800 --> 01:09:28.970
If you look at how power
corrections come in,

01:09:28.970 --> 01:09:31.330
then they're suppressed
because there's

01:09:31.330 --> 01:09:33.580
an ambiguity between power
corrections in perturbation

01:09:33.580 --> 01:09:33.850
theory.

01:09:33.850 --> 01:09:35.260
If the power corrections
are suppressed,

01:09:35.260 --> 01:09:37.069
you have less ambiguity in
the perturbation theory.

01:09:37.069 --> 01:09:38.930
That's another way
of thinking about it.

01:09:38.930 --> 01:09:41.359
But the answer to your question.

01:09:41.359 --> 01:09:45.960
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:45.960 --> 01:09:48.430
IAIN STEWART: It
basically affects this a.

01:09:54.530 --> 01:09:56.070
All right, lots
of good questions.

01:09:56.070 --> 01:09:58.860
Let's see how we get there.

01:09:58.860 --> 01:10:03.200
So when I transform, I'm going
to call the transform function

01:10:03.200 --> 01:10:06.920
capital F, and I'm going to
call its argument B for Borel.

01:10:06.920 --> 01:10:10.760
And so what's the definition
of the Borel transform?

01:10:10.760 --> 01:10:13.740
We're going to
define it as follows.

01:10:13.740 --> 01:10:16.790
There's a first-order
term, and I'm just going

01:10:16.790 --> 01:10:19.220
to put a delta function there.

01:10:19.220 --> 01:10:21.080
The real thing that
matters is the series

01:10:21.080 --> 01:10:23.510
of terms that come next.

01:10:23.510 --> 01:10:27.080
And instead of having F
to the n alpha to the n,

01:10:27.080 --> 01:10:29.970
I'm going to divide by
an extra n factorial,

01:10:29.970 --> 01:10:31.910
and that's the
definition of, given

01:10:31.910 --> 01:10:34.310
a set of F's, how
I construct what's

01:10:34.310 --> 01:10:36.410
called the Borel transform.

01:10:36.410 --> 01:10:44.980
And because of the n factorial,
I get improved convergence,

01:10:44.980 --> 01:10:46.980
so the n factorial is
making it converge better.

01:10:50.570 --> 01:10:54.610
So if there's a transform, there
should be an inverse transform.

01:10:54.610 --> 01:10:57.820
So here's the inverse transform.

01:10:57.820 --> 01:11:04.325
It's an integral from 0 to
infinity, b over alpha F of b.

01:11:16.546 --> 01:11:19.930
And that would get
me back to the F.

01:11:19.930 --> 01:11:22.990
So if you have a
convergent series

01:11:22.990 --> 01:11:24.650
and you think of
this transform, then

01:11:24.650 --> 01:11:26.650
you just can go back and
forth, and you get back

01:11:26.650 --> 01:11:28.930
to the original-- the function
that you started with.

01:11:34.150 --> 01:11:38.000
So if you have some
series that's like that,

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:41.090
you get back--

01:11:41.090 --> 01:11:42.920
you could calculate
that series, and you

01:11:42.920 --> 01:11:46.400
get some F of alpha just
before Borel transforming.

01:11:46.400 --> 01:11:47.930
If you do this Borel
transform, then

01:11:47.930 --> 01:11:51.110
you calculate this
integral, you get back

01:11:51.110 --> 01:11:56.510
the same F of alpha from
the inverse transform.

01:12:05.090 --> 01:12:08.990
Let me give you an
example that shows you

01:12:08.990 --> 01:12:12.710
that, if you have
a divergent series,

01:12:12.710 --> 01:12:15.890
it's not too crazy to define
the sum of the divergent series

01:12:15.890 --> 01:12:19.160
by using these transforms.

01:12:19.160 --> 01:12:22.430
So I claim that, for
a divergent series,

01:12:22.430 --> 01:12:27.825
where F of b and the
inverse transform exist--

01:12:27.825 --> 01:12:29.450
so if we start with
a divergent series,

01:12:29.450 --> 01:12:35.480
but these things exist,
then we could just

01:12:35.480 --> 01:12:39.110
use this transform as a
way of defining F of alpha.

01:12:53.820 --> 01:12:55.520
So let me give you
a simple example

01:12:55.520 --> 01:12:57.350
of that to convince
you that it's not

01:12:57.350 --> 01:12:59.160
such a bad thing to do.

01:12:59.160 --> 01:13:00.785
So let's consider
the following series.

01:13:09.260 --> 01:13:12.570
Just an alternating
series, but alpha

01:13:12.570 --> 01:13:13.820
is a parameter greater than 1.

01:13:16.370 --> 01:13:19.438
That series doesn't converge.

01:13:19.438 --> 01:13:21.605
Of course, for alpha less
than 1, it would converge.

01:13:27.368 --> 01:13:28.910
And if I asked you
what it should be,

01:13:28.910 --> 01:13:31.202
you would say, well, I
calculate for alpha less than 1,

01:13:31.202 --> 01:13:34.970
I analytically continue,
and it's 1 plus alpha.

01:13:34.970 --> 01:13:36.840
Well, that's one way
of getting there.

01:13:36.840 --> 01:13:40.890
Another way of getting there
is using this Borel transform.

01:13:40.890 --> 01:13:47.600
So if you calculate
it here, F of b,

01:13:47.600 --> 01:13:52.585
you sum up 0 to infinity
minus b to the n--

01:13:52.585 --> 01:13:53.960
once you put the
minus 1 in there

01:13:53.960 --> 01:13:56.820
and there's an
extra n factorial.

01:13:56.820 --> 01:14:00.020
So that's e to the minus
b, perfectly well-behaved

01:14:00.020 --> 01:14:01.460
function.

01:14:01.460 --> 01:14:05.380
And then you have to do an
interval, 0 to infinity, db.

01:14:05.380 --> 01:14:09.500
You could have e to the minus
b over alpha times the F of b,

01:14:09.500 --> 01:14:12.860
which is e to the minus
b, and that just gives

01:14:12.860 --> 01:14:15.020
you alpha over 1 plus alpha.

01:14:18.705 --> 01:14:20.580
And this is a perfectly
well-defined interval

01:14:20.580 --> 01:14:23.600
for large alpha.

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:25.670
Large alpha is even
making it better.

01:14:31.850 --> 01:14:33.600
So the integral is
perfectly well-defined,

01:14:33.600 --> 01:14:36.240
and we get an
answer that we like.

01:14:45.630 --> 01:14:48.960
OK, so this Borel
transform is a useful way

01:14:48.960 --> 01:14:52.095
of dealing with
divergent series.

01:15:01.033 --> 01:15:02.450
The real question
is, what happens

01:15:02.450 --> 01:15:04.310
if the inverse
transform doesn't exist?

01:15:13.202 --> 01:15:16.100
And that's what's going
to be the thing that we're

01:15:16.100 --> 01:15:16.910
most interested in.

01:15:34.122 --> 01:15:36.330
So if the F of the integral,
integral over the F of b

01:15:36.330 --> 01:15:43.620
doesn't exist,
then the integrand

01:15:43.620 --> 01:16:02.820
can tell us about the severity
of the singularities, I.e.,

01:16:02.820 --> 01:16:04.697
the severity of the divergence.

01:16:08.680 --> 01:16:12.020
And that's the real power
of this Borel method.

01:16:12.020 --> 01:16:14.390
So let's do another example,
where actually things

01:16:14.390 --> 01:16:15.830
will diverge.

01:16:15.830 --> 01:16:21.580
So let me take F n to be
a to the minus n, n plus k

01:16:21.580 --> 01:16:24.050
factorial.

01:16:24.050 --> 01:16:26.140
And if we do that Borel
transform of that--

01:16:28.660 --> 01:16:32.653
if you have a series,
you can do it.

01:16:32.653 --> 01:16:34.820
And there's only one piece
of it that we care about,

01:16:34.820 --> 01:16:36.403
so I'm just going
to write that piece.

01:16:40.660 --> 01:16:52.130
So there's this piece that has
a kind of pole-like structure,

01:16:52.130 --> 01:16:53.840
and it has a pole at b equals a.

01:16:56.940 --> 01:16:59.760
And what you say is you
call this pole a renormalon.

01:16:59.760 --> 01:17:03.450
This is the renormalon.

01:17:03.450 --> 01:17:05.778
You call it a b
equals a renromalon.

01:17:09.235 --> 01:17:10.860
So you're characterizing
the renormalon

01:17:10.860 --> 01:17:13.120
by where that pole is.

01:17:13.120 --> 01:17:14.940
A renormalon is a
flavor of a particle.

01:17:14.940 --> 01:17:16.998
This has nothing to
do with a particle.

01:17:16.998 --> 01:17:18.540
Usually, you think
of poles as having

01:17:18.540 --> 01:17:19.890
something to do with
particles, and that's

01:17:19.890 --> 01:17:21.000
where the name comes from.

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:21.780
It's due to 't Hooft.

01:17:21.780 --> 01:17:22.290
Blame him.

01:17:22.290 --> 01:17:26.360
[CHUCKLES]

01:17:26.360 --> 01:17:29.780
So if a is less than 0,
your integration contour

01:17:29.780 --> 01:17:32.550
is positive, and the pole
is on the other side,

01:17:32.550 --> 01:17:34.340
so you don't have a problem.

01:17:34.340 --> 01:17:35.840
The inverse transform exists.

01:17:42.710 --> 01:17:44.945
These are called UV renormalons.

01:17:44.945 --> 01:17:46.820
They still can guide
the perturbation theory,

01:17:46.820 --> 01:17:48.650
and they can be
important for thinking

01:17:48.650 --> 01:17:50.150
about why the
perturbation theory is

01:17:50.150 --> 01:17:53.420
behaving the way it is, but you
can do the inverse transform.

01:17:53.420 --> 01:17:56.300
The real ones that are
kind of problematic

01:17:56.300 --> 01:18:00.080
are a greater than 0
because then the pole

01:18:00.080 --> 01:18:04.505
is on the integration contour,
and we can't do the transform.

01:18:12.930 --> 01:18:14.987
So we're integrating d
b from 0 to infinity,

01:18:14.987 --> 01:18:17.570
and we just have a pole sitting
on the axis, so what do we do?

01:18:42.175 --> 01:18:43.800
So you could think
about characterizing

01:18:43.800 --> 01:18:46.200
how poorly behaved a
perturbation theory is

01:18:46.200 --> 01:18:48.330
by looking at these
poles, and that's

01:18:48.330 --> 01:18:51.570
kind of what I meant by having
some kind of notion of how

01:18:51.570 --> 01:18:53.730
divergent a series is.

01:18:53.730 --> 01:19:01.215
So you look in this Borel space,
and you look at the real axis,

01:19:01.215 --> 01:19:06.300
and those poles actually
can be on both sides.

01:19:06.300 --> 01:19:11.490
The most severe pole is the one
that's closest to the origin,

01:19:11.490 --> 01:19:14.130
and that has the
smallest value of b.

01:19:14.130 --> 01:19:17.310
And you can see if you
have a small value of b,

01:19:17.310 --> 01:19:20.200
then you're multiplying here
with some large numbers.

01:19:20.200 --> 01:19:24.180
So if a was 0.1, you'd be
multiplying by 10 to the n.

01:19:24.180 --> 01:19:25.770
So these guys are more severe.

01:19:25.770 --> 01:19:29.100
As you go to larger values,
you get additional suppression

01:19:29.100 --> 01:19:31.860
from this a to the
n, so if a was--

01:19:31.860 --> 01:19:34.860
if you went all the way out to
100, then you'd have 1 over 100

01:19:34.860 --> 01:19:35.550
to the n.

01:19:35.550 --> 01:19:39.100
That's good, but
factorial eventually wins.

01:19:39.100 --> 01:19:42.640
So it's still divergent, but we
look like it was a lot better.

01:19:42.640 --> 01:19:43.140
OK?

01:19:43.140 --> 01:19:46.530
So you can characterize how
severe the series is diverging

01:19:46.530 --> 01:19:49.540
by the location of these poles.

01:19:49.540 --> 01:19:55.770
And you can characterize
the ambiguity

01:19:55.770 --> 01:19:58.650
in doing an integration by--

01:19:58.650 --> 01:20:00.972
if you just think
about one pole,

01:20:00.972 --> 01:20:02.430
you can characterize
the ambiguity,

01:20:02.430 --> 01:20:05.010
so let's just imagine
there's one pole.

01:20:05.010 --> 01:20:06.570
You can characterize
the ambiguity

01:20:06.570 --> 01:20:09.420
by going above or below.

01:20:09.420 --> 01:20:13.770
So you have two possible ways
of defining the interval.

01:20:13.770 --> 01:20:15.720
You don't know which to pick.

01:20:15.720 --> 01:20:16.710
One is to go above.

01:20:19.530 --> 01:20:21.270
The other is to go below.

01:20:27.600 --> 01:20:31.140
And then you can think
about what the ambiguity is.

01:20:31.140 --> 01:20:36.990
And the ambiguity
is the contour 1.

01:20:36.990 --> 01:20:38.620
Call this c1.

01:20:38.620 --> 01:20:39.972
This is c2.

01:20:39.972 --> 01:20:45.570
The ambiguity is c1 minus c2,
and that is circling the pole.

01:20:49.340 --> 01:20:52.220
So you can look at the
residue of the pole,

01:20:52.220 --> 01:20:53.750
and that gives
you the ambiguity.

01:21:02.100 --> 01:21:04.440
So what we'll do
next time is we'll

01:21:04.440 --> 01:21:06.900
look at an example
in perturbative QCD.

01:21:06.900 --> 01:21:09.780
We'll see that there's a
series that has a renormalon,

01:21:09.780 --> 01:21:10.752
and we'll find it.

01:21:10.752 --> 01:21:12.210
And then we'll look
at the residue,

01:21:12.210 --> 01:21:16.710
and we'll find actually that
out will pop lambda QCD.

01:21:16.710 --> 01:21:20.490
So we'll see, we'll calculate,
for some perturbative series,

01:21:20.490 --> 01:21:23.100
that the pole mass really has
an ambiguity of order lambda

01:21:23.100 --> 01:21:26.460
QCD by using this
technique of going around

01:21:26.460 --> 01:21:27.360
a residue of a pole.

01:21:32.410 --> 01:21:33.258
OK?

01:21:33.258 --> 01:21:35.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] when we
say that the b quark has a 4 GV

01:21:35.800 --> 01:21:37.940
mass, what's the mass?

01:21:37.940 --> 01:21:38.440
[INAUDIBLE]

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:40.810
IAIN STEWART: Yeah, so if
you say the b quark has,

01:21:40.810 --> 01:21:43.600
like, 4.2 GV mass,
that's the m s bar mass.

01:21:43.600 --> 01:21:47.770
If you say it has
a 4.73 GV mass,

01:21:47.770 --> 01:21:49.660
that's like the m b 1S mass.

01:21:49.660 --> 01:21:52.325
And if you look at how the
PDG measures the b quark mass,

01:21:52.325 --> 01:21:53.950
they measure it in
one of these schemes

01:21:53.950 --> 01:21:55.690
that I'm telling you
about, like the 1S scheme.

01:21:55.690 --> 01:21:57.190
They [INAUDIBLE]
result for that.

01:21:57.190 --> 01:22:00.970
You can convert between the
1S and the m s bar mass.

01:22:00.970 --> 01:22:03.550
The m s bar mass is a
perfectly well-defined quantity

01:22:03.550 --> 01:22:07.390
it doesn't actually
have a renormalon, OK?

01:22:07.390 --> 01:22:08.530
That's not its problem.

01:22:08.530 --> 01:22:10.420
The pole mass has a renormalon.

01:22:10.420 --> 01:22:13.960
The m s bar mass, its problem
is related to power counting

01:22:13.960 --> 01:22:15.730
in the low-energy theory.

01:22:15.730 --> 01:22:17.560
It's a good mass for
high-energy physics.

01:22:17.560 --> 01:22:19.257
It's a bad mass for
low-energy physics.

01:22:19.257 --> 01:22:20.590
That's the problem with m s bar.

01:22:20.590 --> 01:22:23.050
It's not it's not a technical
problem, that it has a--

01:22:23.050 --> 01:22:27.100
[INAUDIBLE] severity
of renormalon.

01:22:27.100 --> 01:22:28.870
It can have a
higher-order renormalon,

01:22:28.870 --> 01:22:30.995
but it doesn't have the
same severity of renormalon

01:22:30.995 --> 01:22:32.230
as the pole mass.

01:22:32.230 --> 01:22:34.180
The pole mass basically
has the most severe

01:22:34.180 --> 01:22:39.240
possible renormalon, which
is, in some units, 1/2,

01:22:39.240 --> 01:22:40.707
so there's an extra 2 to the n.

01:22:40.707 --> 01:22:42.040
We'll talk about that next time.

01:22:45.972 --> 01:22:48.430
So basically, it's the u equals
1/2 renormalons that really

01:22:48.430 --> 01:22:50.677
are causing a problem in
perturbative [? QCD ?]

01:22:50.677 --> 01:22:52.510
because they're the
most important-- there's

01:22:52.510 --> 01:22:53.990
higher-order ones.

01:22:53.990 --> 01:22:58.060
Even alpha s actually
has a normalon,

01:22:58.060 --> 01:23:00.760
alpha s in the m s
bar scheme, I suspect.

01:23:00.760 --> 01:23:05.420
[CHUCKLES] But even up to
five loops you won't see it,

01:23:05.420 --> 01:23:07.710
or it's very hard to see.

01:23:07.710 --> 01:23:09.500
Let's stop there.